## 1. Purpose
This policy governs how [COMPANY] de-identifies PHI and how it creates and shares **Limited Data Sets (LDS)**, under 45 CFR § 164.514(a)–(e). Properly de-identified data is **not PHI** and is not subject to HIPAA; a Limited Data Set **remains PHI** and may be used/disclosed only for limited purposes under a **Data Use Agreement (DUA)**. This policy ensures [COMPANY] applies the correct method before data is used for analytics, product, or AI/ML.

## 2. Scope
Applies to all PHI processed by [COMPANY] and to all derived datasets, especially those used in [Snowflake] for analytics/reporting and any data used to develop, fine-tune, prompt, or evaluate **machine learning / LLM systems**. Applies to all workforce members and contractors who create or consume such datasets.

## 3. Policy
1. PHI **shall not** be used for analytics, product development, model training/evaluation, or external sharing in identifiable form unless that use is independently permitted (e.g., by the BAA and the Privacy Rule); otherwise it **shall** be **de-identified** or reduced to a **Limited Data Set** first.
2. De-identification **shall** use one of the two regulatory methods only: **Expert Determination** (§ 164.514(b)(1)) or **Safe Harbor** (§ 164.514(b)(2)). No other "best effort" method qualifies.
3. [COMPANY] **shall not** assign a code or other re-identification mechanism that is derived from or related to information about the individual, and **shall not** disclose the re-identification key (§ 164.514(c)).
4. A **Limited Data Set shall** only be used or disclosed for **research, public health, or health care operations**, and only under an executed **Data Use Agreement** (§ 164.514(e)).
5. Re-identification of de-identified data, or attempts to re-identify, **shall** be prohibited except by authorized personnel for an approved purpose, and **shall** be logged.

## 4. Safe Harbor De-Identification (45 CFR § 164.514(b)(2))
Data is de-identified under Safe Harbor when **all 18 identifier categories** are removed for the individual and for relatives, employers, and household members, **and** [COMPANY] has **no actual knowledge** that the remaining information could identify an individual. The 18 identifiers:
1. Names
2. Geographic subdivisions smaller than a state (street, city, county, precinct, ZIP — except the first 3 digits of ZIP under the stated population rule)
3. All date elements (except year) directly related to an individual; all ages over 89 and dates indicating such age aggregated to "90+"
4. Telephone numbers
5. Fax numbers
6. Email addresses
7. Social Security numbers
8. Medical record numbers
9. Health plan beneficiary numbers
10. Account numbers
11. Certificate/license numbers
12. Vehicle identifiers and serial numbers (incl. license plates)
13. Device identifiers and serial numbers
14. Web URLs
15. IP addresses
16. Biometric identifiers (incl. finger and voice prints)
17. Full-face photographs and comparable images
18. Any other unique identifying number, characteristic, or code (except a permitted re-identification code per § 164.514(c))

1. Automated de-identification transforms in [Snowflake] **shall** be reviewed/tested against this list, and a record of the transformation **shall** be retained.
2. "**No actual knowledge**" **shall** be evaluated — free-text fields, rare diagnoses, and small cell sizes can re-identify individuals even after the 18 identifiers are stripped.

## 5. Expert Determination (45 CFR § 164.514(b)(1))
1. A person with **appropriate knowledge of and experience with** generally accepted statistical and scientific principles for de-identification **shall** determine that the risk is **very small** that the information could be used, alone or in combination with other reasonably available information, to identify an individual.
2. The expert **shall** document the **methods and results** of the analysis justifying the determination, and that documentation **shall** be retained for at least **six (6) years**.
3. Expert Determination **shall** be re-validated when the data, linkage environment, or release context materially changes.

## 6. Limited Data Set & Data Use Agreement (45 CFR § 164.514(e))
1. A Limited Data Set excludes the **direct identifiers** listed in § 164.514(e)(2) (e.g., names, addresses other than town/city/state/ZIP, phone/fax, email, SSN, MRN, account/license numbers, vehicle/device IDs, URLs, IPs, biometrics, full-face photos) but **may retain** dates and certain geographic detail — therefore it is **still PHI**.
2. Before disclosing an LDS, [COMPANY] **shall** obtain a **Data Use Agreement** that: establishes permitted uses/disclosures; limits recipients; prohibits re-identification and contact of individuals; requires appropriate safeguards; and binds the recipient's agents/subcontractors (§ 164.514(e)(4)).
3. Executed DUAs **shall** be tracked alongside BAAs (see `baa-management-procedure.md.template` and the vendor/agreement register).

## 7. Analytics & AI/ML Considerations
> **Call-out:** This section is the practical heart of the policy for [COMPANY]'s stack.
1. Datasets feeding [Snowflake] dashboards, BI, or experimentation **shall** default to de-identified data; identifiable PHI in analytics requires explicit approval and a permitted purpose.
2. **LLM / AI usage:** PHI **shall not** be sent to any external/third-party model API or used for training/fine-tuning unless (a) it is de-identified per §4 or §5, or (b) the provider is under a **BAA** and the use is permitted by the originating BAA. Prompts, embeddings, logs, and model outputs can all contain or reconstruct PHI — treat them as PHI until proven de-identified.
3. **Free-text and unstructured data** (clinical notes, support tickets) **shall** be presumed to contain identifiers; Safe Harbor stripping of structured columns alone is insufficient. Use validated redaction plus a "no actual knowledge" review, or Expert Determination, before such data is used for analytics/AI.
4. **Re-identification risk** from joining de-identified data with other [Snowflake] tables or external datasets **shall** be assessed; access to potential linking datasets **shall** be controlled per `minimum-necessary-standard.md.template`.
5. The method, transformations, reviewer, and approval for each de-identified/LDS dataset used in analytics or AI **shall** be documented in [the dataset register].

## 8. Roles & Responsibilities
| Role | Responsibility |
|---|---|
| [Privacy Officer] | Owns this policy; approves de-identification method and LDS/DUA disclosures. |
| [Security Officer] / Data Platform | Implements de-identification/masking transforms in [Snowflake]; controls linking datasets; logs re-identification access. |
| [Qualified Expert / Statistician] | Performs and documents Expert Determinations. |
| Data/Analytics & ML Engineers | Use only approved de-identified/LDS data; do not export PHI to non-BAA tools/models. |
| [Legal / Counsel] | Reviews DUAs and AI/vendor data flows. |

See `../governance/roles-and-responsibilities.md.template` for full role definitions.

## 9. Exceptions
Exceptions require documented risk acceptance per `../governance/exceptions-and-waivers.md.template`, approved by the [Privacy Officer] and [Security Officer], time-bound, and recorded in the exceptions log.

## 10. Compliance, Monitoring & Enforcement
The [Privacy Officer] and data platform team audit dataset lineage, de-identification transforms, DUA coverage, and AI/model data flows. Re-identification attempts and PHI exfiltration to non-approved tools are investigated. Violations are handled per `../people/hr-security-policy.md.template` and the HIPAA workforce sanctions process (`sanctions-policy.md.template`).

